 This is the Lex Friedman Podcast. Support it.

00:43.680 --> 00:45.760
 Please check out our sponsors in the description.

00:46.400 --> 00:49.920
 And now, dear friends, here's Susan Cain.

00:49.920 --> 00:53.040
 You've written on your website that, quote,

00:53.040 --> 00:57.040
 I prefer listening to talking, reading to socializing,

00:57.040 --> 00:59.360
 and cozy chats to group settings.

01:00.080 --> 01:02.640
 So I think this conversation in the podcast is going to be fun.

01:03.360 --> 01:05.760
 What's a good definition of an introvert?

01:05.760 --> 01:09.040
 Is something like those three things a good start?

01:10.080 --> 01:14.800
 It is a good start in terms of how introverts experience day to day life.

01:14.800 --> 01:20.800
 I think a good definition is one that some of your listeners will have heard many times before.

01:20.800 --> 01:23.600
 You know, the idea of where do you get your energy?

01:23.600 --> 01:27.760
 And for some people, they get their energy more from quieter settings,

01:27.760 --> 01:30.320
 and for other people, they get it more from being out there.

01:31.200 --> 01:36.240
 So a good rule of thumb is to imagine that you're at a party that you're really enjoying,

01:36.240 --> 01:38.480
 and you've been there for about two hours or so,

01:38.480 --> 01:42.080
 and it's with people you really like, and it's in your favorite place.

01:42.080 --> 01:42.960
 So it's all good.

01:42.960 --> 01:43.520
 It's all good.

01:44.880 --> 01:49.040
 An extrovert in a setting like that is going to feel charged up,

01:49.040 --> 01:51.280
 and they're going to be looking for the after party.

01:51.280 --> 01:53.840
 And an introvert, no matter how good a time they're having

01:53.840 --> 01:57.840
 and how socially skilled they are, there's this moment where you just wish

01:57.840 --> 02:00.000
 that you could teleport and be back at home.

02:00.560 --> 02:00.880
 Yeah.

02:01.520 --> 02:05.760
 And that the time before the start of the party to the time when that moment happens

02:05.760 --> 02:06.960
 is different for different people.

02:06.960 --> 02:10.480
 So like the shorter that is, the more of an inch where you are, is that that kind of thing?

02:10.480 --> 02:14.560
 The shorter the moment until you get to the place where you've got to teleport home.

02:14.560 --> 02:18.240
 Yeah, and then for extroverts, it's the opposite, right?

02:18.240 --> 02:22.880
 Like they're going to feel, you know, maybe they're working on, I don't know,

02:22.880 --> 02:27.440
 like focused on producing a memo that's really intensely interesting to them.

02:27.440 --> 02:30.240
 But if they're in that state of like solitary,

02:31.200 --> 02:33.280
 the solitary mode of really focusing,

02:33.280 --> 02:36.400
 they might get stir crazy a lot faster than an introvert would.

02:36.400 --> 02:41.840
 And so it doesn't have so much to do with what you're good at as how you get your energy.

02:42.400 --> 02:47.440
 And so for an introvert, the source of energy is what?

02:47.440 --> 02:49.600
 Silence, solitude.

02:49.600 --> 02:52.480
 And for an extrovert, it's interaction with other people.

02:53.040 --> 02:56.480
 What I'd really say is that, and this is neurobiological as well,

02:56.480 --> 03:01.040
 is that it has to do with how your nervous system reacts to stimulation.

03:01.040 --> 03:06.320
 And so for an introvert, you're feeling in a great state of equilibrium

03:06.320 --> 03:09.360
 when there are fewer inputs coming at you.

03:09.360 --> 03:13.440
 So they could be social inputs, but that's why an introvert in general would rather

03:13.440 --> 03:16.880
 like hang out with one close friend at a time as opposed to, you know,

03:16.880 --> 03:20.960
 big party full of strangers, because that's too many inputs for the nervous system.

03:20.960 --> 03:24.480
 And for an extrovert, the nervous system needs more stimulants.

03:24.480 --> 03:28.000
 So if they're not getting enough, they get that listless and sluggish feeling.

03:28.000 --> 03:32.960
 So if you're just walking through the world, like people listening to this,

03:32.960 --> 03:36.240
 but in general, how do you know if you're an introvert?

03:37.040 --> 03:42.800
 Like, how do you empirically start to determine if you are in large part an introvert?

03:43.520 --> 03:47.280
 Well, I would start by just asking that question of what happens to you,

03:47.840 --> 03:50.400
 you know, at around the two hour mark where you're having a good time.

03:50.400 --> 03:55.680
 Yeah, like, I mean imagine, but I also find, I'm curious if you have a different experience

03:55.680 --> 03:59.840
 from this, but from all the years that I've been out there talking about this topic,

03:59.840 --> 04:06.080
 I found that most people really seem to know once they're being honest with themselves.

04:06.080 --> 04:12.000
 And maybe that's the question to ask is like, if you imagine that you have a Saturday or a whole

04:12.000 --> 04:17.920
 weekend where you can spend your time exactly the way you want to with no professional obligations

04:17.920 --> 04:21.200
 and no social obligations, who would you spend it with?

04:21.200 --> 04:22.400
 How many people?

04:22.400 --> 04:23.280
 What would you be doing?

04:23.280 --> 04:27.840
 And what is that picture that you're painting start to look like?

04:27.840 --> 04:35.200
 Yeah, so there's nuance to this though, because I'm sure for extroverts to get energized by

04:35.920 --> 04:40.320
 stimulation, whether that stimulation with other people, like, it depends what that stimulation

04:40.320 --> 04:45.920
 is, right? Like, maybe you're not surrounded by the kind of people that you enjoy being around.

04:45.920 --> 04:53.520
 So, you know, maybe that has to do less with whether some characteristics is your personality,

04:53.520 --> 04:56.480
 more has to do with the fact what like what your environment is like.

04:56.480 --> 04:58.960
 That's always kind of the question.

04:58.960 --> 05:01.600
 Do you want to be alone because everybody around you is an asshole?

05:01.600 --> 05:04.720
 Or do you want to be alone because you get energized from being...

05:04.720 --> 05:07.520
 Well, I would hold the variables constant, I guess, I would say.

05:07.520 --> 05:10.720
 Keep the assholes constant and see.

05:10.720 --> 05:14.800
 And then there's the other thing you kind of observed that there's a lot of people

05:14.800 --> 05:22.160
 that will say they get energized from being alone, like people are exhausting to them or something like that.

05:22.160 --> 05:27.520
 But at the same time, when you see them at a party, they seem like the life of the party.

05:27.520 --> 05:32.720
 I know, and I hear from those people all the time, there's so many people like that.

05:32.720 --> 05:34.800
 What would you classify them as, exactly?

05:34.800 --> 05:38.720
 Is it ultimately as the source of energy, is the most important thing?

05:38.720 --> 05:41.280
 Or like, how the heck are they the life of the party?

05:41.280 --> 05:42.880
 It's a bunch of different things.

05:42.880 --> 05:50.160
 So first of all, just to say, like a big caveat to all of this is humans are just amazingly complex.

05:50.160 --> 05:54.560
 So you can't explain every individual human through these parameters,

05:54.560 --> 05:57.280
 even though I think the parameters are really valuable.

05:57.280 --> 06:02.240
 But that person at the party, it could be that they're more of an ambivert.

06:02.240 --> 06:04.640
 So they kind of are more in the middle of the spectrum.

06:04.640 --> 06:09.120
 It basically means someone who's not extremely introverted or extremely extroverted,

06:09.120 --> 06:10.240
 they're kind of in the middle.

06:10.240 --> 06:13.600
 So maybe at a party, their more extroverted side comes out.

06:13.600 --> 06:21.120
 Or it could be an introvert who's gotten really good at the skills of acting more like a pseudo extrovert.

06:21.120 --> 06:24.560
 And they pull that up at the moments that they need it.

06:24.560 --> 06:26.160
 So they've learned how to fake it.

06:26.160 --> 06:28.320
 Yeah. Oh, there's a lot of people like that.

06:28.320 --> 06:32.080
 And I know this because I think out of all the people on this planet,

06:32.080 --> 06:35.360
 you could be talking to, I've heard from the most number of those people.

06:35.360 --> 06:40.000
 Like they all come and tell me about their experience out in the world,

06:40.000 --> 06:42.960
 presenting a face that's different from what they feel.

06:42.960 --> 06:45.680
 So one of the things you talk about is, at least in the West,

06:45.680 --> 06:48.000
 we've constructed a picture of success.

06:48.000 --> 06:52.320
 And that picture is usually one of an extrovert.

06:52.320 --> 06:56.560
 Like when you imagine somebody who's a leader, who's a successful person,

06:56.560 --> 07:02.480
 that person has some of the qualities you would associate with an extrovert.

07:02.480 --> 07:07.920
 And so there's a lot of incentive for faking it.

07:07.920 --> 07:09.840
 Yeah, exactly.

07:09.840 --> 07:13.200
 If you want to be successful, you've got to be able to fake it,

07:13.200 --> 07:16.320
 to sort of hang with the rest of the team.

07:16.320 --> 07:19.680
 You have to be able to be outgoing and all those kinds of things

07:19.680 --> 07:21.920
 and not be drained by the interaction.

07:21.920 --> 07:24.720
 Yeah, but I mean, there are also a lot of introverts

07:24.720 --> 07:28.080
 who figure out ways to draw on their own strengths.

07:28.080 --> 07:31.840
 And they're incredibly connecting and successful,

07:31.840 --> 07:34.640
 and they're great leaders, and they're not actually faking it.

07:34.640 --> 07:38.000
 They're more just figuring out ways to do it their own way.

07:38.000 --> 07:40.160
 You see a lot of people like that.

07:40.160 --> 07:42.800
 Is there advice, is there lessons you can draw from that,

07:42.800 --> 07:45.760
 from just observing how you can be an introvert

07:45.760 --> 07:48.080
 and be in a leadership position?

07:48.080 --> 07:50.320
 Yeah, it's kind of like a mantra,

07:50.320 --> 07:53.120
 figuring out what your own strengths are and how to draw on them.

07:53.120 --> 07:57.760
 I think of a guy I know, Doug Conant,

07:57.760 --> 08:01.600
 who had been the CEO of Campbell's Soup for many years.

08:01.600 --> 08:03.680
 He's very introverted.

08:03.680 --> 08:06.720
 He's quite shy also by his own description.

08:06.720 --> 08:11.280
 And he really cares about people.

08:11.280 --> 08:15.840
 And so when he started at Campbell,

08:15.840 --> 08:18.320
 the employee engagement ratings of the company

08:18.320 --> 08:21.040
 were all the way at the bottom of the Fortune 500.

08:21.040 --> 08:23.360
 And by the time he stepped down, 10 years later,

08:23.360 --> 08:25.200
 they were all the way at the top.

08:25.200 --> 08:30.960
 And it wasn't that he was going out there and shmoozing people,

08:30.960 --> 08:32.160
 but he really did care.

08:32.160 --> 08:34.160
 So he would find out who were the people

08:34.160 --> 08:35.920
 who had really been contributing,

08:35.920 --> 08:40.560
 and he would write to them personal letters of thanks.

08:40.560 --> 08:45.040
 And these letters meant so much to people.

08:45.040 --> 08:47.280
 They would carry them around with them.

08:47.280 --> 08:49.680
 And during his time, the 10 years of his career

08:49.680 --> 08:51.440
 and during his time, the 10 years there,

08:51.440 --> 08:54.560
 he wrote 30,000 of those letters.

08:54.560 --> 08:56.720
 So that was his way of doing it.

08:56.720 --> 08:58.800
 That was his way of drawing on his own strengths.

08:58.800 --> 09:02.000
 And he did that together with, of course,

09:02.000 --> 09:04.000
 you sometimes have to go outside your comfort zone

09:04.000 --> 09:05.040
 no matter who you are.

09:05.040 --> 09:06.960
 So he was doing plenty of that too.

09:06.960 --> 09:08.480
 It's a kind of combination.

09:08.480 --> 09:11.600
 Yeah, the writing process and focusing

09:11.600 --> 09:15.200
 on the one on one interaction, I can definitely relate.

09:15.200 --> 09:16.800
 There's something deeply draining,

09:16.800 --> 09:19.440
 which concerns me about Zoom meetings,

09:19.440 --> 09:22.640
 because it's some weird brain manipulation.

09:22.640 --> 09:23.520
 Wait, say more.

09:23.520 --> 09:25.920
 Well, because you're not really engaged,

09:26.800 --> 09:30.320
 but it wears on you the same way that it does a party.

09:30.320 --> 09:35.840
 It feels like you're emptying that bucket for the introverts,

09:35.840 --> 09:38.640
 even though they're not participating at all in the meeting.

09:38.640 --> 09:41.200
 I mean, I suppose that's true for physical meetings too,

09:41.200 --> 09:43.520
 but with Zoom meetings or remote meetings,

09:43.520 --> 09:46.240
 it's so much easier to invite a larger number of people

09:46.240 --> 09:47.360
 into the meeting.

09:47.360 --> 09:50.240
 So you're draining more and more of the introvert energy.

09:50.240 --> 09:51.600
 And I'm probably extrovert too,

09:51.600 --> 09:52.800
 but the introvert, definitely.

09:52.800 --> 09:54.320
 There's, I mean, it's interesting.

09:54.320 --> 09:56.160
 I would love to understand that more

09:56.160 --> 09:58.880
 because there's more and more push towards remote work

10:00.400 --> 10:02.800
 without, I think, a deep understanding

10:02.800 --> 10:05.200
 of why these meetings are so draining on people.

10:05.200 --> 10:07.840
 I just anecdotally have heard from that.

10:07.840 --> 10:09.920
 But maybe that's because the managers,

10:09.920 --> 10:11.680
 the people who arrange the meetings,

10:11.680 --> 10:14.560
 are just not sufficiently yet aware

10:14.560 --> 10:16.160
 of the draining nature of them

10:16.160 --> 10:18.080
 so that they pull in too many people.

10:18.080 --> 10:19.520
 They schedule them too regularly,

10:19.520 --> 10:21.680
 so they need to adjust that kind of thing probably.

10:21.680 --> 10:23.680
 I think people are starting to realize,

10:23.680 --> 10:27.600
 but I would say one reason that Zoom is so draining

10:27.600 --> 10:33.040
 is because you can see your own self presentation

10:33.040 --> 10:34.640
 the whole time if you choose to.

10:35.280 --> 10:38.560
 And when you go into in person, you can't.

10:38.560 --> 10:40.960
 So you're kind of freed of thinking about that.

10:40.960 --> 10:42.560
 So it's like an extra cognitive load

10:42.560 --> 10:47.280
 that you're bearing the whole time. Oh yeah, that's brilliant.

10:47.280 --> 10:49.760
 And you might want to turn off the camera

10:49.760 --> 10:51.200
 so you can't see yourself, but then you feel like,

10:51.200 --> 10:53.040
 well, I have the ability to,

10:53.040 --> 10:54.560
 so I probably should be doing it.

10:54.560 --> 10:57.760
 And then that alone is the decision that you're making.

10:57.760 --> 11:00.080
 Yeah, there's probably studies on this now happening,

11:00.080 --> 11:01.680
 either half happen or are happening,

11:02.560 --> 11:07.760
 the effect of seeing your own face on camera

11:07.760 --> 11:09.200
 because it's reminding you that you're supposed

11:09.200 --> 11:10.400
 to be acting a certain way.

11:10.400 --> 11:13.440
 And that is especially a stressful thing.

11:13.440 --> 11:15.360
 Yeah, you can't be in the moment as much.

11:15.360 --> 11:18.160
 But I mean, for you, you make the decision

11:18.160 --> 11:21.840
 to do all your podcast interviews in person, right?

11:21.840 --> 11:22.800
 And so...

11:22.800 --> 11:25.440
 And that's even when it's very costly.

11:26.000 --> 11:28.400
 If there's any kind of chemistry

11:28.400 --> 11:31.200
 that contributes at all to the conversation,

11:31.200 --> 11:34.000
 which I think most conversations have chemistry,

11:34.000 --> 11:37.440
 even the boring work meanings, there's something there.

11:37.440 --> 11:40.320
 Because, yes, you're trying to solve a particular problem

11:40.320 --> 11:43.360
 at this particular time, but underneath it,

11:43.360 --> 11:45.360
 there's a team building that's happening.

11:45.360 --> 11:49.760
 And honestly, people also have told me about this,

11:49.760 --> 11:53.760
 why they enjoyed the Zoom meetings during the pandemic,

11:53.760 --> 11:55.360
 is like, they're lonely.

11:55.360 --> 11:56.400
 Yeah, yeah.

11:56.400 --> 12:00.400
 Like they, you know, it's annoying to have to sit

12:00.400 --> 12:03.120
 and listen to folks talk about nothing and so on.

12:03.120 --> 12:07.280
 But they tune in anyway, because it's kind of

12:07.280 --> 12:08.960
 lonely to sit there by yourself.

12:08.960 --> 12:12.320
 And that, I mean, there's a deep connection there

12:12.320 --> 12:15.440
 with other people, and that is especially true

12:15.440 --> 12:18.560
 when they're in person, which is a huge concern for me

12:18.560 --> 12:22.640
 for more and more offices from a capitalist perspective,

12:23.440 --> 12:27.040
 realizing, hey, why do we have these large office spaces?

12:27.040 --> 12:28.640
 Why do we have to get people together?

12:28.640 --> 12:31.840
 But I think in some deep sounds we do.

12:31.840 --> 12:34.480
 But then you also talk about that once we do,

12:34.480 --> 12:38.000
 we want to protect the introverts.

12:38.000 --> 12:42.080
 Like you don't want the open space, which office space,

12:42.080 --> 12:43.600
 which was a big fad for a while.

12:43.600 --> 12:46.240
 I don't know where people stand on that at this point.

12:46.240 --> 12:47.760
 Yeah, I think people are figuring it out

12:47.760 --> 12:49.360
 in a post pandemic context.

12:49.360 --> 12:51.200
 But I mean, I know what you mean.

12:52.240 --> 12:56.160
 So before I became a writer, I was a corporate lawyer

12:56.160 --> 12:57.680
 for like seven years.

12:57.680 --> 13:01.760
 And literally the only thing I miss from those years

13:01.760 --> 13:05.760
 is hanging out with people at the office.

13:05.760 --> 13:08.400
 Like, I don't know, just some of the funniest moments

13:08.400 --> 13:11.920
 I've had in my life came from being at the office

13:11.920 --> 13:14.240
 until midnight with the other people I was working with.

13:14.240 --> 13:15.760
 So I know exactly what you're talking about.

13:15.760 --> 13:18.400
 So I will say the office is there at that firm

13:18.400 --> 13:20.000
 and at most firms in those days,

13:20.000 --> 13:21.360
 everybody had their own office.

13:21.360 --> 13:22.960
 So it was like a dorm room, you know,

13:22.960 --> 13:24.160
 where it was like a long hallway

13:24.160 --> 13:26.400
 with everybody in their own little dorm room.

13:26.400 --> 13:29.520
 So you had tons of privacy, but you would also come out

13:29.520 --> 13:31.360
 and hang out with people.

13:31.360 --> 13:33.760
 You could just kind of roam whenever you want.

13:34.480 --> 13:35.280
 Yeah, yeah.

13:35.280 --> 13:37.600
 And whenever you roam, that means you're kind of open.

13:38.640 --> 13:39.600
 You're looking for trouble.

13:40.960 --> 13:42.000
 You're open for interaction.

13:42.000 --> 13:44.160
 And the extent to which you would keep your door open,

13:44.160 --> 13:46.320
 you know, was it wide open or was it half a jar

13:46.320 --> 13:48.400
 or just a little bit, those were all signals.

13:49.360 --> 13:51.200
 So is there, because you said reenergize,

13:51.200 --> 13:52.960
 is there, do you like to think,

13:52.960 --> 13:54.720
 and again, the human mind is complicated,

13:54.720 --> 13:57.040
 but do you like to think of it as like a bucket

13:57.040 --> 13:59.440
 that gets refilled for introverts

13:59.440 --> 14:03.520
 in terms of energy of social interaction

14:03.520 --> 14:06.800
 that they're able to handle?

14:07.440 --> 14:10.080
 Do you think of it like that as a bucket

14:10.080 --> 14:12.080
 that gets emptied and needs to be refilled?

14:12.080 --> 14:13.360
 I think of it, yeah, more or less,

14:13.360 --> 14:15.200
 because I use the metaphor of a battery

14:15.200 --> 14:16.720
 that gets recharged or not.

14:16.720 --> 14:18.960
 It's basically the same thing, different metaphor.

14:19.680 --> 14:21.200
 But yeah, but just to add on that,

14:21.840 --> 14:23.920
 there is a layer of complexity to that

14:23.920 --> 14:27.760
 because you could be somebody who

14:27.760 --> 14:30.960
 doesn't want the kind of social life, let's say,

14:30.960 --> 14:33.760
 where you have to be like on and presenting

14:33.760 --> 14:35.760
 and interacting with tons of people all the time,

14:35.760 --> 14:38.080
 but you'd get really lonely if you were just by yourself.

14:38.080 --> 14:40.880
 You know, so what you want is to maybe be in the company

14:40.880 --> 14:42.640
 of a couple of people you know really well.

14:43.520 --> 14:46.160
 Like for me, the pandemic was not actually that hard

14:46.160 --> 14:47.200
 for me personally.

14:47.200 --> 14:49.200
 I mean, I lost family, but I mean,

14:49.200 --> 14:51.200
 from the point of view of what we're talking about,

14:51.200 --> 14:54.000
 it wasn't that hard because I live with my husband

14:54.000 --> 14:55.200
 and my kids.

14:55.200 --> 14:58.560
 So I knew it was hard on the kids and I felt badly for them.

14:58.560 --> 15:00.880
 But for me, I was like, you know what,

15:00.880 --> 15:03.280
 I kind of, I have a lot of social life right here

15:03.280 --> 15:05.920
 in the house and I can focus and do my work.

15:05.920 --> 15:07.760
 Yeah, yeah.

15:07.760 --> 15:10.160
 That's the cool thing about the pandemic.

15:10.160 --> 15:11.520
 I think it helped people figure out

15:11.520 --> 15:13.120
 how much they love their family.

15:13.120 --> 15:14.160
 I think that's true.

15:14.160 --> 15:15.920
 And a lot of you give you a chance

15:15.920 --> 15:18.880
 to really reconnect with kids, with your kids,

15:18.880 --> 15:20.560
 like really spend time with them.

15:20.560 --> 15:21.760
 It's just fascinating to watch.

15:21.760 --> 15:23.440
 Like people actually, it did,

15:23.440 --> 15:28.160
 strengthen the family unit in an often beautiful way,

15:28.160 --> 15:32.160
 which just sucks to have to leave behind at this point.

15:32.160 --> 15:34.560
 Yeah, and I think that's part of what people are not

15:34.560 --> 15:37.840
 going to want to go back to that we need to solve for

15:37.840 --> 15:41.200
 to the extent that work becomes non remote again.

15:41.200 --> 15:42.000
 Yeah.

15:42.000 --> 15:43.680
