 So yeah, there might, there might be other things you're totally blind to, I guess that's

1:41:04.640 --> 1:41:05.640
 possible.

1:41:05.640 --> 1:41:10.160
 But that's the way of parenting is you solve the problems of the past, but there's another

1:41:10.160 --> 1:41:11.160
 new one.

1:41:11.160 --> 1:41:15.000
 I guess I'll find out in 120 years, but like so far, so good.

1:41:15.000 --> 1:41:20.480
 What wisdom about parenting can you give from your own experience and from your writing?

1:41:20.480 --> 1:41:24.400
 Yeah, well, oh my God, there's a lot to say.

1:41:24.400 --> 1:41:33.720
 So on the bittersweet side of things, the wisdom that I would give is that especially

1:41:33.720 --> 1:41:42.080
 for kids who are growing up in relative comfort with everything going pretty well, they get

1:41:42.080 --> 1:41:49.280
 the idea that real life is when things are going well, and when things don't go well,

1:41:49.280 --> 1:41:54.360
 it's like a detour from the main road, as opposed to understanding that it's all the

1:41:54.360 --> 1:41:55.360
 main road.

1:41:55.360 --> 1:42:02.080
 And I tell the story in the book of this time that we went on this family vacation where

1:42:02.080 --> 1:42:08.240
 we rented a house in the countryside, and the house was next to this field where lived

1:42:08.240 --> 1:42:13.360
 two donkeys that our kids fell in love with, and they were like really little at the time,

1:42:13.360 --> 1:42:14.360
 two boys.

1:42:14.360 --> 1:42:19.120
 And they're spending all this time feeding carrots to the donkeys, and it's all beautiful.

1:42:19.120 --> 1:42:22.960
 And then comes the day where they realized that we're leaving in like two days, and they're

1:42:22.960 --> 1:42:25.040
 never going to see these donkeys again.

1:42:25.040 --> 1:42:27.440
 And they start crying themselves to sleep.

1:42:27.440 --> 1:42:32.720
 And the usual things that parents might say at a moment like that of like, maybe we'll

1:42:32.720 --> 1:42:37.800
 come back or another family will feed them, we'll feed these donkeys, none of that made

1:42:37.800 --> 1:42:39.800
 any difference.

1:42:39.800 --> 1:42:48.680
 But when we said to them, goodbye is part of life, and this feeling you're having, everybody

1:42:48.680 --> 1:42:53.040
 has it, you've had it before, you're going to have it again, you'll feel better in a

1:42:53.040 --> 1:42:58.360
 couple of days, but this is the way it's supposed to be, this is natural.

1:42:58.360 --> 1:43:03.520
 That's when they stopped crying, because I think that's when they stopped resisting.

1:43:03.520 --> 1:43:04.520
 Yeah.

1:43:04.520 --> 1:43:08.920
 Like it's one thing to feel the pain of goodbye, and it's another thing to be feeling like

1:43:08.920 --> 1:43:11.720
 this isn't supposed to be happening.

1:43:11.720 --> 1:43:16.160
 It's the resistance part of this isn't supposed to be happening that makes life really difficult.

1:43:16.160 --> 1:43:17.160
 Yeah.

1:43:17.160 --> 1:43:19.840
 As opposed to a more clear eyed view of what it really is.

1:43:19.840 --> 1:43:21.680
 This isn't supposed to be happening.

1:43:21.680 --> 1:43:24.760
 There's a show called Yellowstone, I recently started watching.

1:43:24.760 --> 1:43:25.760
 Yeah.

1:43:25.760 --> 1:43:26.760
 No, I've heard of it.

1:43:26.760 --> 1:43:30.000
 We actually started watching it, but only a few minutes and didn't get into it.

1:43:30.000 --> 1:43:34.920
 So there's just a quick, it's not a spoiler of any kind, but there's a father taking

1:43:34.920 --> 1:43:40.120
 out the son for the first time to go hunting and to shoot their first buck.

1:43:40.120 --> 1:43:46.280
 And the son is really sad because he pulls a trigger and he took a life.

1:43:46.280 --> 1:43:51.840
 And the father says that everybody gets killed in this life.

1:43:51.840 --> 1:43:53.160
 That's the way of nature.

1:43:53.160 --> 1:43:57.280
 That's the way each one of us is going to get killed.

1:43:57.280 --> 1:44:03.000
 And it's interesting because I didn't really think of it that way because you think you

1:44:03.000 --> 1:44:10.760
 die, but he really framed it as killed because he's like, there's no such thing as dying

1:44:10.760 --> 1:44:12.160
 of old age.

1:44:12.160 --> 1:44:17.840
 That's medically, let's discuss that a bit, but basically there's something, whether it's

1:44:17.840 --> 1:44:26.120
 a truck or a bacteria, something's going to kill you in the end.

1:44:26.120 --> 1:44:32.960
 And that was an interesting way to look at it because we tend to think of humans aren't

1:44:32.960 --> 1:44:34.120
 supposed to be killed.

1:44:34.120 --> 1:44:39.120
 We think of murder as one of the things that you don't do in society.

1:44:39.120 --> 1:44:44.840
 But you know what, we do, that's a more technical discussion whether we ultimately get killed

1:44:44.840 --> 1:44:49.560
 by something in the end, but to some degree that's true, at least for most of us, that

1:44:49.560 --> 1:44:53.800
 there's something that gets us, whether it's cancer, those kinds of things.

1:44:53.800 --> 1:44:54.800
 It's interesting.

1:44:54.800 --> 1:44:59.840
 But yeah, that reframing of it's supposed to be this is the way of the world.

1:44:59.840 --> 1:45:00.840
 Yeah.

1:45:00.840 --> 1:45:01.840
 Though it's funny.

1:45:01.840 --> 1:45:05.640
 I mean, at the same time that I just wrote a whole book about the fact that this is the

1:45:05.640 --> 1:45:06.640
 way it is.

1:45:06.640 --> 1:45:11.520
 I really do believe this is the way it is and with this reality, there's an intense beauty

1:45:11.520 --> 1:45:16.080
 that comes along with it, so we have to accept the reality to get to the beauty.

1:45:16.080 --> 1:45:17.080
 I believe that.

1:45:17.080 --> 1:45:22.200
 And at the same time, there's a part of me that's just like, yeah, but give me the magic

1:45:22.200 --> 1:45:24.520
 wand to make the world different.

1:45:24.520 --> 1:45:25.520
 Yeah.

1:45:25.520 --> 1:45:26.520
 Yeah.

1:45:26.520 --> 1:45:27.520
 Yeah.

1:45:27.520 --> 1:45:28.520
 I don't know.

1:45:28.520 --> 1:45:30.040
 I don't know how much of this is a female thing too.

1:45:30.040 --> 1:45:34.120
 Like I was watching with my son, my 12 year old the other day, we were watching this show

1:45:34.120 --> 1:45:44.920
 about the battle of Thermopylae, and it was all about valor and glory on the battlefield.

1:45:44.920 --> 1:45:51.400
 And I said to him something like, gosh, don't you just wish we lived in a world where you

1:45:51.400 --> 1:45:54.920
 didn't have to do all this in order for everyone just to live their lives?

1:45:54.920 --> 1:45:58.000
 And he just looked at me completely puzzled.

1:45:58.000 --> 1:45:59.000
 Like, no.

1:45:59.000 --> 1:46:04.360
 To him, it all just seemed self evident that the world would be structured that way.

1:46:04.360 --> 1:46:09.840
 And he had the 12 year old admiration for the valor of it all.

1:46:09.840 --> 1:46:17.240
 But you wonder if that's nature or nurture.

1:46:17.240 --> 1:46:21.280
 I wonder what that world looks like.

1:46:21.280 --> 1:46:26.000
 We do live in a world where murder is seen as bad, but you look at a lot of the human

1:46:26.000 --> 1:46:27.000
 history.

1:46:27.000 --> 1:46:30.960
 I don't know if they had the same kind of conception of that.

1:46:30.960 --> 1:46:38.640
 In terms of, you have to ask what kind of murder for what purpose?

1:46:38.640 --> 1:46:41.760
 War was a way of life.

1:46:41.760 --> 1:46:42.760
 It's interesting.

1:46:42.760 --> 1:46:51.560
 It's interesting if we can imagine properly a future that is different than ours in terms

1:46:51.560 --> 1:46:53.560
 of operating under the different moral systems.

1:46:53.560 --> 1:47:01.960
 But I'd like the same with living indefinitely or living in a society with no war.

1:47:01.960 --> 1:47:04.360
 Like how fundamental is war?

1:47:04.360 --> 1:47:05.360
 How fundamental is death?

1:47:05.360 --> 1:47:08.640
 I mean, I think it's so fundamental to our source code.

1:47:08.640 --> 1:47:10.960
 I just wish that our source code were different, basically.

1:47:10.960 --> 1:47:14.960
 Well, it's people working on that, right?

1:47:14.960 --> 1:47:18.640
 There's brain computer interfaces that try to merge.

1:47:18.640 --> 1:47:24.080
 So greater and greater, we have smartphones, we're already cyborgs, but greater and greater

1:47:24.080 --> 1:47:27.000
 merger of computational power.

1:47:27.000 --> 1:47:33.600
 So literally adding source code to our original source code, there's the mushy biology that

1:47:33.600 --> 1:47:40.880
 runs source code, and then there's more cold electrical systems, and then they integrate

1:47:40.880 --> 1:47:41.880
 together.

1:47:41.880 --> 1:47:50.000
 So actually, one day, we offload the magic that is human consciousness also into the

1:47:50.000 --> 1:47:52.320
 machine, and then we'll get to see.

1:47:52.320 --> 1:47:58.520
 Maybe there'll be a little bit less assholeish about the whole war thing, there'd be more.

1:47:58.520 --> 1:48:05.000
 But there is, I think, even when I think about engineering human intelligence or superhuman

1:48:05.000 --> 1:48:10.200
 intelligence systems, I feel like they also need to have the yin and yang of life.

1:48:10.200 --> 1:48:15.760
 They have to be able to be afraid and to be sad and all those kinds of things.

1:48:15.760 --> 1:48:20.080
 But maybe it's because I'm a product in this particular environment.

1:48:20.080 --> 1:48:26.680
 Maybe sadness is a human, useful human invention, but not a universal one.

1:48:26.680 --> 1:48:30.840
 This is what I don't know, because this is where I come back to the, as I told you, like

1:48:30.840 --> 1:48:36.040
 the original reason that I wrote my whole book was the feeling that somehow in the expression

1:48:36.040 --> 1:48:42.000
 of sad music is what other people see when they talk about God, like there's something

1:48:42.000 --> 1:48:48.600
 so, there's like an ultimate beauty there that I don't know if we have access to without

1:48:48.600 --> 1:48:49.600
 that.

1:48:49.600 --> 1:48:50.600
 But maybe we do.

1:48:50.600 --> 1:48:55.560
 But I can say in this world, that's a great way to get access to that state.

1:48:55.560 --> 1:49:00.080
 Is it within the reach of science or deeply understand this, you think, to understand

1:49:00.080 --> 1:49:02.720
 that why you feel sad when you're listening to a song?

1:49:02.720 --> 1:49:05.680
 Or why you feel so much love when you're listening to a sad song?

1:49:05.680 --> 1:49:07.560
 Do a sad song, right?

1:49:07.560 --> 1:49:15.600
 Why the sad song opens up some kind of deep connection to something you can call divine

1:49:15.600 --> 1:49:17.520
 or something, whatever the heck that is.

1:49:17.520 --> 1:49:19.160
 Yeah, I do think.

1:49:19.160 --> 1:49:24.280
 I mean, we have like really early signs of it from the research, and I'm sure we're just

1:49:24.280 --> 1:49:27.160
 at the scratching the surface stage.

1:49:27.160 --> 1:49:32.960
 But I mean, like we know, for example, that the vagus nerve, which is so fundamental that

1:49:32.960 --> 1:49:38.880
 it governs our breathing and our digestion, our vagus nerve also activates when we see

1:49:38.880 --> 1:49:46.680
 another being in distress, there's like an instinctive impulse to want to make it stop.

1:49:46.680 --> 1:49:51.520
 And the theory is that that's an evolutionary design, because we had to be able to respond

1:49:51.520 --> 1:49:56.920
 to the cries of our infants, you know, and from that ability grows the greater ability

1:49:56.920 --> 1:49:59.920
 to respond to other people's cries too.

1:49:59.920 --> 1:50:07.040
 So that's probably just, you know, the very first step in being able to understand what

1:50:07.040 --> 1:50:08.720
 all that is.

1:50:08.720 --> 1:50:13.120
 We've already given plenty of advice, but broadly, what advice would you give to young

1:50:13.120 --> 1:50:21.760
 folks today about career, about life, whether they want to be writers, lawyers, scientists,

1:50:21.760 --> 1:50:26.520
 musicians, and artists, whatever the heck they want to be, how can they live a life

1:50:26.520 --> 1:50:28.000
 they can be proud of?

1:50:28.000 --> 1:50:29.000
 Okay.

1:50:29.000 --> 1:50:38.680
 I think you should absolutely do that thing that you're dying to do.

1:50:38.680 --> 1:50:46.480
 But you should always have a plan B, like a backup plan and a way of earning a living,

1:50:46.480 --> 1:50:53.800
 no matter what happens, because I feel like people, we have this narrative in our culture

1:50:53.800 --> 1:51:00.480
 of like that the glamorous thing is to figure out the thing you love and then risk everything

1:51:00.480 --> 1:51:02.480
 to achieve that.

1:51:02.480 --> 1:51:06.000
 But first of all, a lot of people aren't comfortable with that level of risk.

1:51:06.000 --> 1:51:11.120
 And second, when you're living with that level of risk, that's a cognitive load too.

1:51:11.120 --> 1:51:15.760
 And so you don't have the full emotion and heart to be able to focus on the thing that

1:51:15.760 --> 1:51:19.000
 you actually really love, because you're like stressed out about it.

1:51:19.000 --> 1:51:23.960
 So I'd say like get the backup plan in place and then do the thing.

1:51:23.960 --> 1:51:25.480
 My advice would be the opposite.

1:51:25.480 --> 1:51:26.480
 Okay.

1:51:26.480 --> 1:51:27.480
 Tell me why.

1:51:27.480 --> 1:51:28.480
 I'm moving the romantic.

1:51:28.480 --> 1:51:37.760
 Well, I think the best, the truth is be aware of the cost not having a plan B has, so do

1:51:37.760 --> 1:51:40.160
 it deliberately if you don't.

1:51:40.160 --> 1:51:44.760
 But I, you know, I'm with Bukowski on find what you love and let it kill you.

1:51:44.760 --> 1:51:48.200
 I think you have to actually know your personality.

1:51:48.200 --> 1:51:55.480
 I know if I have a plan B, I will not try as hard on plan A. And I would likely take

1:51:55.480 --> 1:52:03.560
 plan B because if plan A is the risky thing, I just work way much better when in the state

1:52:03.560 --> 1:52:04.560
 of desperation.

1:52:04.560 --> 1:52:05.560
 Okay.

1:52:05.560 --> 1:52:08.160
 So with my back against the wall and you have to know that about yourself.

1:52:08.160 --> 1:52:09.160
 I think that has to do with...

1:52:09.160 --> 1:52:13.280
 So I think we can refine it to say you actually have to really know yourself and how you respond

1:52:13.280 --> 1:52:15.120
 to different kinds of risks.

1:52:15.120 --> 1:52:17.560
 Like I would not do well in that kind of situation.

1:52:17.560 --> 1:52:23.160
 I'd be like up at two in the morning, worrying about it, whereas if I have some, like it

1:52:23.160 --> 1:52:27.480
 doesn't have to be paying the rent in some grand way, but if there's some basic way of

1:52:27.480 --> 1:52:31.400
 paying the rent, then my heart's free to do the thing I really love.

1:52:31.400 --> 1:52:32.400
 That's hilarious.

1:52:32.400 --> 1:52:39.400
 I, for me, the only way I'm free is when I don't know how I'm going to pay the rent.

1:52:39.400 --> 1:52:40.400
 Huh.

1:52:40.400 --> 1:52:41.400
 Yeah.

1:52:41.400 --> 1:52:48.440
 Because otherwise I'll find a way to pay the rent that's not at all a source of deep fulfillment

1:52:48.440 --> 1:52:49.440
 for me.

1:52:49.440 --> 1:52:50.440
 I see.

1:52:50.440 --> 1:52:53.840
 So it's like if you don't have like the, what's the expression?

1:52:53.840 --> 1:52:57.720
 I don't know, something like the dog at your back, then you won't actually do it.

1:52:57.720 --> 1:53:01.680
 I create real or artificial deadlines, anxiety and so on.

1:53:01.680 --> 1:53:03.720
 So yeah, you have to...

1:53:03.720 --> 1:53:04.720
 Yeah.

1:53:04.720 --> 1:53:09.840
 So really the advice is know your triggers, but we're still saying the same basic thing

1:53:09.840 --> 1:53:14.720
 of like, do the thing you really love, but just set up the rest of your life.

1:53:14.720 --> 1:53:15.720
 The strategy is the rest of your life.

1:53:15.720 --> 1:53:16.720
 Yeah.

1:53:16.720 --> 1:53:17.720
 Yeah.

1:53:17.720 --> 1:53:18.720
 Exactly.

1:53:18.720 --> 1:53:19.720
 Exactly.

1:53:19.720 --> 1:53:21.960
 What do you think is the meaning of life?

1:53:21.960 --> 1:53:25.120
 The meaning of this whole thing?

1:53:25.120 --> 1:53:31.360
 Probably has something to do with whatever we feel when we listen to a sad song.

1:53:31.360 --> 1:53:32.360
 Yeah.

1:53:32.360 --> 1:53:37.720
 I, because two things come simultaneously to my mind when you ask that question and

1:53:37.720 --> 1:53:42.800
 I've been asking it since I was four, I remember the first time I did.

1:53:42.800 --> 1:53:45.080
 The question is more important than the answer probably.

1:53:45.080 --> 1:53:46.080
 Yeah.

1:53:46.080 --> 1:53:47.080
 Just keep asking.

1:53:47.080 --> 1:53:48.080
 I don't know.

1:53:48.080 --> 1:53:51.360
 The first one is beauty and I don't know why beauty is so important, but I just know that

1:53:51.360 --> 1:53:52.360
 it is.

1:53:52.360 --> 1:53:54.920
 And impossible to define perhaps.

1:53:54.920 --> 1:53:55.920
 Is it definable?

1:53:55.920 --> 1:53:56.920
 Yeah.

1:53:56.920 --> 1:53:59.960
 Other than you know it when you see it.

1:53:59.960 --> 1:54:00.960
 I don't know.

1:54:00.960 --> 1:54:01.960
 I mean, just...

1:54:01.960 --> 1:54:08.440
 It has to do with that line that you feel something when you just see it, when you hear it.

1:54:08.440 --> 1:54:09.440
 Yeah.

1:54:09.440 --> 1:54:14.760
 You just see it and it's like, like some, it's whatever can deliver you to that mode

1:54:14.760 --> 1:54:22.760
 of transcendence where you're no longer purely in your own self and you're in something higher.

1:54:22.760 --> 1:54:30.240
 And when you're in those states of mind, you know it because you have the temporary sensation

1:54:30.240 --> 1:54:35.040
 that you could die at that moment, that the people you love could die and it will all

1:54:35.040 --> 1:54:39.640
 be okay because there's something else.

1:54:39.640 --> 1:54:40.640
 So that's my first answer.

1:54:40.640 --> 1:54:41.640
 Beauty.

1:54:41.640 --> 1:54:47.840
 And then my second answer is the need to relieve psychic pain, like other people's psychic

1:54:47.840 --> 1:54:48.840
 pain.

1:54:48.840 --> 1:54:49.840
 I don't know why.

1:54:49.840 --> 1:54:51.800
 That's just, that's just like an impulse that I have.

1:54:51.800 --> 1:54:55.360
 Psychic pain is more like, like suffering of any form.

1:54:55.360 --> 1:54:56.360
 What is that?

1:54:56.360 --> 1:54:57.360
 Yeah.

1:54:57.360 --> 1:54:58.560
 But I mean...

1:54:58.560 --> 1:54:59.560
 Is there a particular...

1:54:59.560 --> 1:55:00.560
 Yeah.

1:55:00.560 --> 1:55:08.360
 Just making the world better and less pain, less pain to go around in general.

1:55:08.360 --> 1:55:16.040
 Hence your sort of optimistic desire and longing for a world without sort of destruction, without

1:55:16.040 --> 1:55:19.040
 malevolent destruction.

1:55:19.040 --> 1:55:20.040
 Yeah.

1:55:20.040 --> 1:55:22.160
 A world where that wouldn't be necessary.

1:55:22.160 --> 1:55:23.160
 Yeah.

1:55:23.160 --> 1:55:24.160
 Exactly.

1:55:24.160 --> 1:55:25.160
 Exactly.

1:55:25.160 --> 1:55:28.080
 But yeah, like I, so I had this moment.

1:55:28.080 --> 1:55:29.080
 It wasn't so long ago.

1:55:29.080 --> 1:55:34.320
 I was doing some interview and somebody asked me, like, what are you longing for right now?

1:55:34.320 --> 1:55:39.040
 And my answer at that moment was like, you know what, I'm actually at this moment in

1:55:39.040 --> 1:55:41.560
 life where I'm not longing for anything.

1:55:41.560 --> 1:55:46.760
 I'm at this particular way station where everything is the way I want it to be.

1:55:46.760 --> 1:55:51.920
 And of course, the minute you say something like that, you know, you're going to be proven

1:55:51.920 --> 1:55:57.560
 wrong because like an hour later, I get a letter from a reader who I've been in touch

1:55:57.560 --> 1:56:03.080
 with over the years and he was telling me about like a psychic struggle that he's going

1:56:03.080 --> 1:56:04.080
 through.

1:56:04.080 --> 1:56:09.760
 And I just felt like, oh my gosh, if there were anything I could do to make it that his

1:56:09.760 --> 1:56:13.360
 life wouldn't have been such that he would be in this position in the first place, like

1:56:13.360 --> 1:56:17.480
 his struggles had to do with a long life history.

1:56:17.480 --> 1:56:22.360
 So I don't know why I feel that so intently, but I do.

1:56:22.360 --> 1:56:27.440
 Those moments when you are just at peace, there's nothing else you want, feel like that's

1:56:27.440 --> 1:56:30.360
 like a temporary repose, like a pause.

1:56:30.360 --> 1:56:32.880
 Exactly.

1:56:32.880 --> 1:56:39.000
 You bet your ass a desire follows that at some point, but you get to enjoy those little

1:56:39.000 --> 1:56:40.000
 moments.

1:56:40.000 --> 1:56:41.000
 Yeah.

1:56:41.000 --> 1:56:44.400
 And even when he asked me and I answered that way, I said, this is a way station, like

1:56:44.400 --> 1:56:49.760
 I knew it was temporary, but I didn't realize it would be disrupted like an hour later.

1:56:49.760 --> 1:56:58.520
 And that sort of to give you pushback to your, to your statement about the possibility of

1:56:58.520 --> 1:57:04.360
 you can see a beauty and basically alleviating suffering is a quote I really like from Hunter

1:57:04.360 --> 1:57:10.000
 S. Thompson that pushes back against that, which is for every moment of triumph for every

